hands_on_practices.solution:
1. The first‐order displacement amplitude $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{r}}_s$ is related to the velocity amplitude $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{v}}_s$ by 
$$\boldsymbol{\mathcal{v}}_s=-i\omega\,\boldsymbol{\mathcal{r}}_s\quad\Longrightarrow\quad 
\boldsymbol{\mathcal{r}}_s=\frac{\boldsymbol{\mathcal{v}}_s}{-i\omega}
=\frac{i}{\omega}\frac{i q E_0(x)}{m_s(\omega-\Omega_s)}(\hat{\mathbf{x}}+i\hat{\mathbf{y}})
=-\frac{qE_0(x)}{m_s\,\omega(\omega-\Omega_s)}(\hat{\mathbf{x}}+i\hat{\mathbf{y}})\,. $$

2. The ponderomotive force is 
$$\mathbf{F}_{p,s}=\tfrac12\Re\bigl[q(\boldsymbol{\mathcal{r}}_s^*\!\cdot\nabla)\boldsymbol{\mathcal{E}}_1\bigr]\,,\quad 
\boldsymbol{\mathcal{E}}_1=E_0(x)(\hat{\mathbf{x}}+i\hat{\mathbf{y}})\,. $$

3. Since the field amplitude only varies with $x$, the gradient operator becomes $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{r}}_s^*\!\cdot\nabla = \mathcal{r}_{s,x}^* \frac{d}{dx}$.
$$(\boldsymbol{\mathcal{r}}_s^*\!\cdot\nabla)\boldsymbol{\mathcal{E}}_1
=\mathcal{r}_{s,x}^*\,\frac{dE_0}{dx}(\hat{\mathbf{x}}+i\hat{\mathbf{y}})
=-\frac{qE_0}{m_s\,\omega(\omega-\Omega_s)}\frac{dE_0}{dx}(\hat{\mathbf{x}}+i\hat{\mathbf{y}})\,. $$

4. Substituting this into the force expression:
$$\mathbf{F}_{p,s}
=\frac12\Re\!\Bigl[-\frac{q^2E_0}{m_s\,\omega(\omega-\Omega_s)}\frac{dE_0}{dx}(\hat{\mathbf{x}}+i\hat{\mathbf{y}})\Bigr]
=-\frac{q^2}{2m_s\,\omega(\omega-\Omega_s)}
E_0\frac{dE_0}{dx}\,\hat{\mathbf{x}}
=-\frac{q^2}{4m_s\,\omega(\omega-\Omega_s)}\frac{d}{dx}(E_0^2)\,\hat{\mathbf{x}}\,.
$$

5. Taking magnitudes and forming the ratio,
$$R=\frac{|\mathbf{F}_{p,A}|}{|\mathbf{F}_{p,B}|}
=\frac{\displaystyle\frac{q^2}{4m_A\,|\omega(\omega-\Omega_A)|}}
{\displaystyle\frac{q^2}{4m_B\,|\omega(\omega-\Omega_B)|}}
=\frac{m_B}{m_A}\frac{|\omega-\Omega_B|}{|\omega-\Omega_A|}
=\alpha\frac{|\omega-\Omega_B|}{|\omega-\Omega_A|}\,. $$

6. Using $\Omega_B=\Omega_A/\alpha$ and $\omega=\sqrt{\Omega_A\Omega_B}=\Omega_A/\sqrt\alpha$,
$$\omega-\Omega_A=\Omega_A\Bigl(\tfrac1{\sqrt\alpha}-1\Bigr),\qquad
\omega-\Omega_B=\Omega_A\Bigl(\tfrac1{\sqrt\alpha}-\tfrac1\alpha\Bigr)
=\Omega_A\frac{\sqrt\alpha-1}{\alpha}\,. $$
Since $\alpha > 1$, $\omega-\Omega_A$ is negative and $\omega-\Omega_B$ is positive. Taking absolute values:
$$\frac{|\omega-\Omega_B|}{|\omega-\Omega_A|}
=\frac{\Omega_A(\sqrt\alpha-1)/\alpha}{\Omega_A(1-1/\sqrt\alpha)}
=\frac{(\sqrt\alpha-1)/\alpha}{(\sqrt\alpha-1)/\sqrt\alpha}
=\frac{1}{\sqrt\alpha}\,. $$
Finally, the force ratio is:
$$R=\alpha\cdot\frac1{\sqrt\alpha}=\sqrt\alpha\,. $$
